"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:2.17\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">2.17</span> Standard, ensign, banner</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אוֹת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’oth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:2\">NUM 2:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps74:4\">PSA 74:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps74:4\">PSA 74:4</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">דגל</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(dagal (verb))</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps20:6\">PSA 20:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Song6:4\">SNG 6:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Song6:10\">SNG 6:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">דֶּגֶל</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(degel)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num1:52\">NUM 1:52</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:2\">NUM 2:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:3\">NUM 2:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:10\">NUM 2:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:17\">NUM 2:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:18\">NUM 2:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:25\">NUM 2:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:31\">NUM 2:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num2:34\">NUM 2:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num10:14\">NUM 10:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num10:18\">NUM 10:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num10:22\">NUM 10:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num10:25\">NUM 10:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Song2:4\">SNG 2:4</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">נֵס</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(nes)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod17:15\">EXO 17:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num21:8\">NUM 21:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num21:9\">NUM 21:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps60:6\">PSA 60:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa5:26\">ISA 5:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa11:10\">ISA 11:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa11:12\">ISA 11:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa13:2\">ISA 13:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa18:3\">ISA 18:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:17\">ISA 30:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa31:9\">ISA 31:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa49:22\">ISA 49:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa62:10\">ISA 62:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer4:6\">JER 4:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer4:21\">JER 4:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer50:2\">JER 50:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer51:12\">JER 51:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer51:27\">JER 51:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek27:7\">EZK 27:7</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">נסס</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(nasas (verb))</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech9:16\">ZEC 9:16</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">תֹּרֶן</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(toren)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa30:17\">ISA 30:17</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0394_standards.png\" alt=\"Various examples of standards\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Various examples of standards (Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature, Harper 1888, Public domain)</figcaption></figure>The standard was a distinctive device used to identify a particular group. It could be a flag or a board attached to a stick. In many cases it was a metal device or image (such as an eagle or the head of a lion) that was fitted over the end of a pole in much the same way that a spearhead was attached to a spear.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0395_standards_en.jpg\" alt=\"Reconstruction of the Titus Arch frieze (Rome), showing a menorah and standards from the temple being carried off by the Roman victors (71 C.E.)\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Reconstruction of the Titus Arch frieze (Rome), showing a menorah and standards from the temple being carried off by the Roman victors (71 C.E.) (© Original file by Steerpike (File:Arch of Titus Menorah.png), CC BY 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The Hebrew words listed above occur in both military and religious contexts. In a time of war the standard was carried with the army into combat and served as a rallying point for the soldiers. If a victory was won or a strategic position was captured, the standard might be set up in that place as a sign of victory. So in a language where flags or military standards are unfamiliar, it is possible to say the following in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps74:4\">PSA 74:4</a>: “they have placed their signs of victory here” or “they have put up the signs that show they have defeated us.”</p>\n<p>There is a textual problem in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod17:16\">EXO 17:16</a>. While the Hebrew text reads <em>kes</em>, meaning “seat” or “throne,” some translations accept an emended text that reads <em>nes</em>, which appears also in the previous verse; for example, for the first half of this verse <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> has “He said, ‘Hold high the banner of the LORD!’ ” Other translations prefer to translate the word <em>kes</em> without emendation; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr> has “He said, ‘For hands were lifted up to the throne of the LORD.’ ”</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech9:16\">ZEC 9:16</a>: The precise meaning of the Hebrew verb form <em>mithnossoth</em> is doubtful. If it is related to the word <em>nes</em>, then the literal meaning is “lifted up as an ensign.” However, very few translations (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"King James Version (1611)\">KJV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New American Bible (1970)\">NAB</abbr>, Vulgate) express this meaning. Most translators and commentators take the word to be related to a different Hebrew root meaning “to shine” or “to sparkle.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
